{"title_page": "Andrew Breitbart", "text_new": "{{short description|Conservative writer and publisher}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Andrew Breitbart\n| image              = Andrew Breitbart by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Breitbart at [[Conservative Political Action Conference|CPAC]] in 2012, 3 weeks before his death\n| birth_name         = Andrew James Breitbart\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1969|02|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2012|03|01|1969|02|01}}\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| resting_place      = [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| occupation         = Writer, columnist, journalist, publisher\n| alma_mater         = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Susannah Bean|1997}}\n| children           = 4\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.breitbart.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Breitbart''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|a\u026a|t|b|\u0251r|t}}; February 1, 1969 \u2013 March 1, 2012) was an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist,<ref name=\"c-span\"/> writer, and commentator who was the founder of [[Breitbart News]].\n\nAfter helping in the early stages of ''[[HuffPost]]''<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/Breitbart.com-has-Drudge-to-thank-for-its-success---page-2/2100-1025_3-5976096-2.html |title=Breitbart.com has Drudge to thank for its success |accessdate=July 29, 2009 |publisher=Cnet news |date=November 2005}}</ref> and the ''[[Drudge Report]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=Christina|title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337#.UCsmqJZSTsY|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> Breitbart created ''[[Breitbart News]]'', a news and right-wing opinion website, along with multiple other \"BIG\" sites - BIGHollywood, BIGGovernment, BIGJournalism. He played central roles in the [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|Anthony Weiner sexting scandal]], the [[firing of Shirley Sherrod]], and the [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alternet.org/story/154463/what_really_killed_andrew_breitbart_the_likely_cause_of_death_the_mainstream_media_ignored|title=What Really Killed Andrew Breitbart? The Likely Cause of Death The Mainstream Media Ignored|last=Roshan|first=Maer|date=March 8, 2012|work=AlterNet|access-date=August 22, 2017|last2=Slayton|first2=Hunter R.}}</ref> Commenters such as [[Nick Gillespie]] and [[Conor Friedersdorf]] have credited Breitbart with changing how people wrote about politics by \"show[ing] how the Internet could be used to route around information bottlenecks imposed by official spokesmen and legacy news outlets\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 2, 2012|first=Nick|last=Gillespie}}</ref><ref name=Atlantic1>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/03/andrew-breitbarts-legacy-credit-and-blame-where-its-due/253953/ | title=Andrew Breitbart's Legacy: Credit and Blame Where It's Due | publisher=Atlantic Media | work=Politics | date=March 8, 2012 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Friedersdorf, Connor}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBreitbart was born in [[Los Angeles]] on February 1, 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last1=Peters |first1=Jeremy W.|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was the adopted son of Gerald and Arlene Breitbart, a restaurant owner and banker respectively, and grew up in the affluent neighborhood of [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\" /> He was adopted at three weeks old and raised [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/940/000203331/#FN1|title=Andrew Breitbart|publisher=NNDB|page=1|language=English|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> His biological parents had been [[Irish American]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/andrew-breitbart-built-internet-empire-by-combining-new-media-old-fashioned-pranks/2012/03/01/gIQA7vc9kR_story.html|title=Andrew Breitbart built Internet empire by combining new media, partisan slant|last=Farhi|first=Paul|date=March 1, 2012|publisher=The Washington Post|language=English|accessdate=August 16, 2017|location=United States}}</ref> He said that his birth certificate indicated his biological father was a folk singer. His adoptive mother had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Judaism when marrying his adoptive father.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.single.html |title=Big Breitbart: Andrew Breitbart is messing with you | author= Christopher Beam |journal =Slate Magazine |accessdate=March 17, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100322191051/http://www.slate.com/id/2247593| archivedate= March 22, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion |title=The Weekend Interview With Andrew Breitbart: Taking On the 'Democrat-Media Complex' |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=October 18, 2009 | first=James | last=Taranto | date=October 16, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091020224720/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362.html?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion| archivedate= October 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Breitbart studied at [[Hebrew school]] and had a [[Bar Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Breitbart, Republican Jewish media mogul, is dead at 43|first=Jonah|last=Lowenfeld|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/thenon-prophet/item/andrew_breitbart_republican_jewish_media_mogul_is_dead_at_43_20120301}}</ref> Theologically he was an agnostic.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart attended [[Brentwood School (Los Angeles)|Brentwood School]], one of the country's top private schools, but did not distinguish himself, saying: \"My sense of humor saved me\".<ref name=\"family\"/> However, he discovered that he loved writing, publishing his first comedic piece in the school newspaper, the ''Brentwood Eagle'', analyzing the inequality in his high school's senior and junior parking lots: \"One had Mercedes and BMWs, the other Sciroccos and GTIs.\"\"<ref name=\"family\"/> Breitbart remembers his upbringing as [[apolitical]], except in one instance: when the family's rabbi tried to defend [[Jesse Jackson]] against charges of antisemitism after his \"[[Hymietown]]\" comment, his parents left the synagogue in protest.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart would remain \"proudly and playfully Jewish\" throughout his life, although not always religiously observant. He would sing Hebrew songs at work while also teasing his Orthodox Jewish colleagues for keeping a kosher diet.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/Comment-Andrew-Breitbart-Israel-and-Judaism \"Comment: Andrew Breitbart, Israel and Judaism\"] By Benjamin Weinthal, ''Jerusalem Post'', April 3, 2012</ref> [[Joel Pollak]] wrote: \"He carried his faith as he carried all his convictions: with a lighthearted touch but a deep commitment.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/> Breitbart later said of his profession: \"I'm glad I've become a journalist because I'd like to fight on behalf of the Israeli people... And the Israeli people, I adore and I love.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/><ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/politics/article/andrew_breitbart_the_unabashedly_biased_journalist_20110613/ \"Andrew Breitbart, the unabashedly 'biased journalist'\u201d] by Jonah Lowenfeld, June 13, 2011, ''Jewish Journal''</ref>\n\nWhile in high school, Breitbart worked as a [[pizza delivery]] driver; he sometimes delivered to celebrities such as [[Judge Reinhold]].<ref>''Righteous Indignation'', page 17</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[American studies]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1991, graduating with \"no sense of [his] future whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/29/20070529-111812-9136r/print/|title='News addict' gets his fix|last=McCain|first=Robert Stacy|date=May 29, 2007|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> His early jobs included a stint at [[cable television|cable]] channel [[E! Entertainment Television]], working for the company's [[blog|online magazine]], and some time in film production.<ref name=\"wsj\"/> He was a Lincoln Fellow at [[Claremont Institute|The Claremont Institute]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|last=DeVore|first=Chuck|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2012/mar/01/andrew-breitbart-most-important-conservative|title=The most important conservative of our time never to hold office {{!}} Chuck DeVore|date=2012-03-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.claremont.org/page/fellowships/lincoln-fellowship/former-lincoln-fellows/|title=Lincoln Fellowship Alumni|website=www.claremont.org|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nPreviously left-leaning in his politics, Breitbart changed his political views after experiencing \"an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]]\" while watching the late 1991 [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|confirmation hearings]] for Supreme Court justice [[Clarence Thomas]], due to what he considered unfounded attacks on the part of liberals based on former employee [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment accusations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aim.org/podcast/take-aim-andrew-breitbart/|title= Take AIM: Andrew Breitbart }}</ref> Breitbart later described himself as \"a [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] conservative\" with [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] sympathies.<ref name=\"c-span\"/>\n\nListening to radio hosts such as [[Rush Limbaugh]] helped Breitbart refine his political and philosophical positions, igniting an interest in learning that he had suppressed as a result of his distaste for the \"nihilistic musings of dead [[critical theory|critical theorists]]\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\">Righteous Indignation, p. 36</ref> that had dominated his studies at Tulane. In this era, Breitbart also read [[Camille Paglia]]'s book ''[[Sexual Personae]]'' (1990), a massive survey of Western art, literature and culture from ancient Egypt to the 20th century, which, he wrote, \"made me realize how little I really had learned in college.\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\"/>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===Authorship, research, and reporting===\nBreitbart has been lauded for his role in the \"evolution of pioneering websites\" including ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and ''[[Drudge Report|The Drudge Report]]'', and later his \"Big\" sites. Journalists such as Nick Gillespie and Conor Friedersdorf have credited Breitbart with bringing new voices to debates about politics and culture. Breitbart told ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' in 2004 that after feeling ignored by existing outlets, \"We decided to go out and create our media.\" Described as \"a series of do-it-yourself demonstration projects\" and \"conversation pits\", the Breitbart websites have been both criticized and praised for their role in various political issues.<ref name=Atlantic1 /><ref name=\"Gillespie\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|date=March 2, 2012|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=January 4, 2015|author=Gillespie, Nick}}</ref> Breitbart has been recognized for adopting an inclusive stance with regard to LGBT participation in the conservative movement. He has also been credited with helping to derail [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories about Barack Obama's citizenship]].<ref name=Atlantic1 />\n\nIn 1995, Breitbart saw ''The Drudge Report'' and was so impressed that he e-mailed [[Matt Drudge]]. Breitbart said, \"I thought what he was doing was by far the coolest thing on the Internet. And I still do.\"<ref name=\"huff\" /> Breitbart described himself as \"Matt Drudge's [[bitch (insult)#In reference to men|bitch]]\"<ref name=\"biyatch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html|title=Lists: What's Your Source for That? Where Andrew Breitbart gets his information.|accessdate=October 1, 2008|publisher=ReasonOnline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919111403/http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html| archivedate= September 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> and selected and posted links to other news wire sources. Later, Drudge introduced him to a then still-[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Arianna Huffington]]<ref name=\"wsj\" /> and Breitbart subsequently assisted in the creation of ''The Huffington Post''.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Andrew Breitbart Helped Launch Huffington Post|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/how-andrew-breitbart-helped-launch-huffington-post|publisher=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBreitbart wrote a weekly column for ''[[The Washington Times]]'', which also appeared at [[Real Clear Politics]]. Breitbart also co-wrote the book ''[[Hollywood, Interrupted|Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon]]'' with [[Mark Ebner]], a book that is highly critical of U.S. [[celebrity culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |title=Wiley: Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity \u2013 Andrew Breitbart, Mark Ebner |work=wiley.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705051111/http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |archivedate=July 5, 2009 }}</ref> On January 19, 2011, the [[LGBT conservatism|conservative gay rights]] group [[GOProud]] announced Breitbart had joined its Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%E2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803200215/http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%e2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 3, 2011 |title=Conservative Media Mogul Andrew Breitbart to Join GOProud's Advisory Council |publisher=Goproud.org |date=January 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Grand Central Publishing released Breitbart's book ''Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World'', in which he discussed his own political evolution and the part he took in the rise of [[new media]], most notably at the Drudge Report and ''The Huffington Post''.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Breitbart's websites broke the story that congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] was [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandal|sending women revealing photographs of himself]].<ref>Daly, Corbett D. [http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20069298-503544.html \"Conservative website posts private pictures of Anthony Weiner.\"] [[CBS News]]. June 6, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Breitbart.com===\n{{main|Breitbart News Network}}\nBreitbart launched his first website as a news site; it is often linked to by the ''[[Drudge Report]]'' and other websites. It has wire stories from the [[Associated Press]], [[Reuters]], [[Agence France-Presse]], [[Fox News]], [[PR Newswire]], and [[U.S. Newswire]], as well as direct links to a number of major international newspapers. Its political viewpoint as well as its audience runs to the [[right-wing|right]] within the U.S. political spectrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.org/interactives/media-polarization/outlet/breitbart/|title=Where Breitbart's Audience Fits on the Political Spectrum |date=October 21, 2014|work=Pew Research Center's Journalism Project}}</ref> In 2007, Breitbart launched a video blog, Breitbart.tv.<ref>[[Rob Owen (journalist)|Owen, Rob]]. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07075/769897-96.stm The next wave: Ex-WTAE anchor Scott Baker changes channel to run Web news site], ''[[Post-Gazette]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart and one of his editors [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] were sued for [[defamation]] by [[Shirley Sherrod]], who had been [[Firing of Shirley Sherrod|fired]] after Breitbart posted a video of a speech given by Sherrod. The video had been selectively edited to suggest that she had purposely discriminated against a white farmer, while in reality the unedited video told the story of how she had helped that farmer.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Zeleny| first = Jeff|author2=  Wheaton, Sarah| title = At Gathering, Ron Paul Is No. 1 for 2012| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]| pages = A21 | date = February 13, 2011| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/us/politics/13cpac.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | accessdate =February 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein\" /> Breitbart himself maintained that he stated this in his article about it, and that the purpose of the video was to show the crowd's positive reaction to Sherrod's statements about discriminating against the white farmer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/128436-andrew-breitbart/ |title= Breitbart on ACORN, Sherrod, and 'Gotcha' Journalism |author=Stephen Reader |date= May 11, 2011}}</ref> In July 2015, it was reported that Sherrod and Breitbart's estate had reached a tentative settlement.<ref name=\"Gerstein\">{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Breitbart, Sherrod near libel settlement|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/breitbart-sherrod-near-libel-settlement-209824.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It was reported October 1, 2016, that the lawsuit was settled.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://talkingpointsmemo.com/muckraker/sherrod-breitbart-lawsuit-settle |title= Ex-USDA Official Settles Her Lawsuit Over Breitbart Video That Got Her Fired |work= [[Talking Points Memo]] |author= Tierney Sneed |date= October 1, 2015 |accessdate= October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commentaries===\nIn 2009, Breitbart appeared as a commentator on ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'' and ''[[Dennis Miller]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BREITBART: 'My Real Time With Bill Maher'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/16/my-real-time-with-bill-maher/?page=all|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=March 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he was a guest commentator on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News Channel's]] morning show and frequently appeared as a guest panelist on [[Fox News]]'s late night program, ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]''. Breitbart also appeared as a commentator in the 2004 documentary ''[[Michael Moore Hates America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/212271/michael-wilson-loves-america/andrew-leigh |title=National Review Online|publisher=nationalreview.com |accessdate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2009, Breitbart appeared on the [[C-SPAN]] program ''[[Washington Journal]]''. He gave his opinions on the mainstream media, Hollywood, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama Administration]] and his personal political views, having heated debates with several callers.<ref name=\"c-span\">[http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 Andrew Breitbart, Breitbart.com Publisher] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002155759/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 |date=October 2, 2012 }} [[C-SPAN]], October 22, 2009. Breitbart referred to the \"Democrat-media complex\" several times...</ref>\n\nIn the hours immediately following Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]'s death, Breitbart called Kennedy a \"villain\", a \"duplicitous bastard\", a \"prick\"<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html|title=Not all Kennedy critics hold fire|accessdate=August 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090827091650/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html| archivedate= August 27, 2009| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"a special pile of human excrement,\" adding, \"Sorry, he destroyed lives. And he knew it,\" referring to Kennedy's actions during the [[Chappaquiddick incident]], the [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination]], and the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination]].<ref>\"[http://www.pennlive.com/editorials/index.ssf/2009/08/compromise_what_pennsylvania_l.html Compromise: what Pennsylvania lawmakers could learn from Ted Kennedy]\" (editorial), ''[[The Patriot-News]]'' (Pennsylvania), August 28, 2009. Retrieved September 24, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320 |title=Opinion: Ted Kennedy, the liberal adversary to the conservative movement |publisher=digitaljournal.com |accessdate=September 24, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003110202/http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320| archivedate= October 3, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Breitbart received the [[Reed Irvine]] [[Accuracy in Media]] Award during the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in Washington, D.C. During his acceptance speech, he responded directly to accusations by ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporter Kate Zernike that [[Jason Mattera]], a young conservative activist, had been using \"racial tones\" in his [[allusions]] to President [[Barack Obama]], and had spoken in a \"[[Chris Rock]] voice\". From the podium, Breitbart called Zernike \"a despicable human being\" for having made such allegations about what, according to him, was just Mattera's Brooklyn accent.<ref>Beam, Christopher, [http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.html \"'Media Is Everything. It's Everything.' Slate's 2010 profile of Andrew Breitbart\"], ''Slate.com'', March 15, 2010.</ref> At the same conference, Breitbart was also filmed saying to journalist [[Max Blumenthal]] that he found him to be \"a jerk\" and \"a despicable human being\" over a blog entry in which Blumenthal accused Breitbart of employing a racist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MIeByOeERpY |title=Max Blumenthal confronted by Andrew Breitbart and Larry O'Connor/Stage right at CPAC 10 |publisher=YouTube |date=February 20, 2010 |accessdate=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Blumenthal was referring to [[James O'Keefe]] over his having attended a [[Georgetown Law Center]] discussion on race featuring Kevin Martin, [[John Derbyshire]], and [[Jared Taylor]], the last of whom founded ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', an online magazine often considered white supremacist. Neither O'Keefe nor Breitbart endorsed Taylor's views.\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart said that \"of course\" [[Donald Trump]] was not a conservative, adding:\n\n<blockquote>But this is a message to those candidates who are languishing at 2 percent and 3 percent within the Republican Party who are brand names in Washington, but the rest of the country don't know ... celebrity is everything in this country. And if these guys don't learn how to play the media the way that Barack Obama played the media last election cycle and the way that Donald Trump is playing the election cycle, we're going to probably get a celebrity candidate.<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\">{{cite news|last1=Weigel|first1=David|title=Five things to know about Breitbart, the new force in the Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/17/five-things-to-know-about-breitbart-the-new-force-in-the-trump-campaign/|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThese comments resurfaced after the controversy of Donald Trump hiring [[Breitbart News]]' executive chairman [[Steve Bannon]] to be his [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\" />\n\n===Activism===\n{{See also|Tea party movement#Reports of slurs at health care reform protests|l1=Tea Party movement}}\nBreitbart often appeared as a speaker at [[Tea Party movement]] events across the U.S. For example, Breitbart was a speaker at the first National Tea Party Convention at Gaylord Opryland Hotel in Nashville on February 6, 2010.<ref>\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_D2YLnaTr6w/ Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, February 2010]{{dead link|date=March 2012 | Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, January]\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N3os3js4B0/ Part 2]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3t6XSeR5GEw/ Part 3]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jJZmKGE6tdE/ Part 4]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> Breitbart later involved himself in a controversy over allegations of [[homophobia|homophobic]] and [[racism|racial]] slurs being used at a March 20, 2010, rally at the [[United States Capitol]] in Washington, D.C., by asserting that slurs were never used, and that \"it was a set-up\" by [[Nancy Pelosi]] and the Democratic Party. Breitbart offered to donate $100,000 to the [[United Negro College Fund]] \"for any audio/video footage of the [[nigger|N-word]] being hurled,\" claiming that the several Congressmen made it up. Breitbart insisted Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] and several other witnesses were forced to lie, concluding that \"Nancy Pelosi did a great disservice to a great civil rights icon by thrusting him out there to perform this mischievous task. His reputation is now on the line as a result of her desperation to take down the Tea Party movement.\"<ref name=\"AB-100402\">{{cite web |url=http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |title=Barack Obama's Helter-Skelter, Insane Clown Posse, Alinsky Plans to 'Deconstruct' America |first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |publisher=Big Journalism |date=April 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302143429/http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |archivedate=March 2, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WPost Omb\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/09/AR2010040903716.html|title=Allegations of spitting and slurs at Capitol protest merit more reporting|date=April 11, 2010|work=Washington Post|accessdate=April 14, 2010| first=Andrew |last=Alexander}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a [[YouTube]] video showed Breitbart yelling at [[Occupy D.C.]] protesters outside a Washington hotel hosting a [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC). The video showed security escorting Breitbart back to the hotel while he told the protesters to \"behave yourself\", and alluding to reported assaults of women at Occupy encampments, he repeatedly yelled, \"Stop raping people\", and called the protestors \"filthy, filthy, raping, murdering freaks!\" David Carr said with the incident Breitbart had caused his last \"viral storm on the Web.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html?pagewanted=all |work=The New York Times |first=David |last=Carr |title=The Life and Death of Andrew Breitbart |date=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=CPAC>Sources that describe the confrontation with Occupy protesters at CPAC 2012:\n* [http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2012/02/web-talking-about-andrew-breitbarts-occupy-DC-freakout/48598/ The Web is Talking About Andrew Breitbart's Occupy D.C. Freakout], by Seth Abramovitch, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', February 12, 2012\n* [http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2012/02/11/eighty_seven_seconds_of_andrew_breitbart_yelling.html Eighty-Seven Seconds of Andrew Breitbart Yelling], by David Weigel, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', February 11, 2012\n* [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers WATCH: Andrew Breitbart LOSES It On Occupy Wall Street Protesters]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212021939/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers |date=December 12, 2012 }}, by Grace Wyler, ''[[Business Insider]]'', March 6, 2012\n* [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/03/01/andrew-breitbart-dies-most-controversial-moments-video.html Andrew Breitbart Dies: Most Controversial Moments (Video)], by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://www.observer.com/2012/03/andrew-breitbart-dead-03012012/ Andrew Breitbart Dead at 43], by Kat Stoeffel and Hunter Walker, ''[[The New York Observer]]'', January 3, 2012\n* [http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ EXCLUSIVE VIDEO: Blogger Andrew Breitbart to Occupiers: 'Stop Raping People!']   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419075311/http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ |date=April 19, 2012 }}, by Emily Crockett, ''[[Campus Progress]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/andrew-breitbart-confronts-occupy-crowd-at-cpac-demands-they-stop-raping-people/ Andrew Breitbart Confronts Occupy Crowd At CPAC, Demands They 'Stop Raping People'], by Frances Martel, ''[[Mediaite]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php Right-Wing Blog Mogul Andrew Breitbart Flips Out at Occupy D.C. Outside CPAC]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212061609/http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php |date=February 12, 2012 }}, by Benjamin R. Freed, ''[[DCist]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php Occupiers Berated By Breitbart; ''Times'' Looks At Movement's Next Moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413053517/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php |date=April 13, 2012 }}, by Esther Zuckerman, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', February 11, 2012</ref>\n\nBreitbart appeared posthumously in ''[[Occupy Unmasked]]'', a documentary film by [[Steve Bannon]] that contends that the [[Occupy movement|Occupy Wall Street movement]] of \"largely na\u00efve students and legitimately concerned citizens looking for answers\" is actually orchestrated by sinister, violent, and organized leaders with the purpose of not just changing, but destroying the American government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Occupyunmasked.com|url=http://www.occupyunmasked.com/about.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBreitbart was married to Susannah Bean, the daughter of actor [[Orson Bean]] and fashion designer Carolyn Maxwell, and had four children.<ref name=\"huff\"/><ref name=\"Saad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-orson-bean-2050-story.html |first1=Nardine |last1=Saad |date=February 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=OBITUARIES Actor Orson Bean, local theater mainstay who rose to fame as a 1950s TV personality, dies |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AP\"> {{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-114135652.html |title=Celebrity Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 8, 2020|via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of February 29, 2012, Breitbart collapsed suddenly while walking in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]]. He was rushed to [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]], where he was pronounced dead just after midnight, March 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html |title=The Provocateur | publisher =New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Celebs/breitbart,%20andrew_report.pdf |title=Andrew Breitbart autopsy report | publisher =Autopsyfile.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337\n |title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead\n |first=Christina |last=Ng |date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> He was 43 years old. An [[autopsy]] by the [[Los Angeles County Coroner's Office]] showed that he had [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]], with focal coronary [[atherosclerosis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/05/commentator-and-editor-andrew-breitbart-died-of-heart-failure-and-hard-up-to-a-60-narrowing-of-a-major-artery-and-was-unde.html|title=Andrew Breitbart died of heart failure, narrowing of artery, coroner finds|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|work=L.A. Times|publisher=L.A. Times|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and died of a [[heart attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|date=2012-03-01|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His burial was in the Jewish cemetery [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery|Hillside Memorial Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew James Breitbart |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/86040288/andrew-james-breitbart |website=Find A Grave\u2122 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn remembrance, Republican presidential candidates [[Rick Santorum]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Newt Gingrich]] praised Breitbart.<ref name=\"media star\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/03/06/limbaugh-and-the-gop-the-media-stars-and-politics/agdmwrt/?page=3|title=Limbaugh and the GOP: The media stars and politics|author=Beth Fouhey|author2=Philip Elliott|work=Associated Press|date=March 6, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> Santorum called Breitbart's death \"a huge loss\" that strongly affected him.<ref name=\"media star\"/><ref>{{cite video |date=March 1, 2012 |title=CBS News|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/andrew-breitbart-death-shocks-santorum-100/2012/03/01/gIQAqm8qkR_video.html}}</ref> Romney praised Breitbart as a \"fearless conservative,\" while Gingrich remembered him as \"the most innovative pioneer in conservative activist social media in America\".<ref name=\"media star\" /> A special episode of ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]'' aired the day after his death as the host and panelists paid their tributes and showed clips from his appearances on the show.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CLqEPe9emsU |title=Red Eye Remembers Andrew Breitbart |accessdate= September 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|title = Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World|publisher = [[Grand Central Publishing]]|date = April 15, 2011|isbn = 978-0-446-57282-8|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/righteousindigna0000brei|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first = Mark C.|last =  Ebner|authorlink = Mark Ebner |author2=Andrew Breitbart |title = [[Hollywood, Interrupted]]: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|date = March 10, 2005|isbn = 978-0-471-70624-3}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q503917|q=Andrew Breitbart|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|c=category:Andrew Breitbart}}\n* {{IMDb name|1620485}}\n* {{C-SPAN|andrewbreitbart}}\n* {{Worldcat id|id=lccn-no2004-14171}}\n* {{Find a Grave|86040288}}\n\n{{Andrew Breitbart|state=expanded}}\n{{Portalbar|Biography|California|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breitbart, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American alternative journalists]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American online journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Breitbart News people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:HuffPost]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish agnostics]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Conservative writer and publisher}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Andrew Breitbart\n| image              = Andrew Breitbart by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Breitbart at [[Conservative Political Action Conference|CPAC]] in 2012, 3 weeks before his death\n| birth_name         = Andrew James Breitbart\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1969|02|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2012|03|01|1969|02|01}}\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| resting_place      = [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| occupation         = Writer, columnist, journalist, publisher\n| alma_mater         = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Susannah Bean|1997}}\n| children           = 4\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.breitbart.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Breitbart''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|a\u026a|t|b|\u0251r|t}}; February 1, 1969 \u2013 March 1, 2012) was an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist,<ref name=\"c-span\"/> writer, and commentator who was the founder of [[Breitbart News]].\n\nAfter helping in the early stages of ''[[HuffPost]]''<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/Breitbart.com-has-Drudge-to-thank-for-its-success---page-2/2100-1025_3-5976096-2.html |title=Breitbart.com has Drudge to thank for its success |accessdate=July 29, 2009 |publisher=Cnet news |date=November 2005}}</ref> and the ''[[Drudge Report]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=Christina|title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337#.UCsmqJZSTsY|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> Breitbart created ''[[Breitbart News]]'', a news and right-wing opinion website, along with multiple other \"BIG\" sites - BIGHollywood, BIGGovernment, BIGJournalism. He played central roles in the [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|Anthony Weiner sexting scandal]], the [[firing of Shirley Sherrod]], and the [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alternet.org/story/154463/what_really_killed_andrew_breitbart_the_likely_cause_of_death_the_mainstream_media_ignored|title=What Really Killed Andrew Breitbart? The Likely Cause of Death The Mainstream Media Ignored|last=Roshan|first=Maer|date=March 8, 2012|work=AlterNet|access-date=August 22, 2017|last2=Slayton|first2=Hunter R.}}</ref> Commenters such as [[Nick Gillespie]] and [[Conor Friedersdorf]] have credited Breitbart with changing how people wrote about politics by \"show[ing] how the Internet could be used to route around information bottlenecks imposed by official spokesmen and legacy news outlets\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 2, 2012|first=Nick|last=Gillespie}}</ref> .<ref name=Atlantic1>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/03/andrew-breitbarts-legacy-credit-and-blame-where-its-due/253953/ | title=Andrew Breitbart's Legacy: Credit and Blame Where It's Due | publisher=Atlantic Media | work=Politics | date=March 8, 2012 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Friedersdorf, Connor}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBreitbart was born in [[Los Angeles]] on February 1, 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last1=Peters |first1=Jeremy W.|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was the adopted son of Gerald and Arlene Breitbart, a restaurant owner and banker respectively, and grew up in the affluent neighborhood of [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\" /> He was adopted at three weeks old and raised [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/940/000203331/#FN1|title=Andrew Breitbart|publisher=NNDB|page=1|language=English|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> His biological parents had been [[Irish American]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/andrew-breitbart-built-internet-empire-by-combining-new-media-old-fashioned-pranks/2012/03/01/gIQA7vc9kR_story.html|title=Andrew Breitbart built Internet empire by combining new media, partisan slant|last=Farhi|first=Paul|date=March 1, 2012|publisher=The Washington Post|language=English|accessdate=August 16, 2017|location=United States}}</ref> He said that his birth certificate indicated his biological father was a folk singer. His adoptive mother had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Judaism when marrying his adoptive father.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.single.html |title=Big Breitbart: Andrew Breitbart is messing with you | author= Christopher Beam |journal =Slate Magazine |accessdate=March 17, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100322191051/http://www.slate.com/id/2247593| archivedate= March 22, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion |title=The Weekend Interview With Andrew Breitbart: Taking On the 'Democrat-Media Complex' |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=October 18, 2009 | first=James | last=Taranto | date=October 16, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091020224720/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362.html?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion| archivedate= October 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Breitbart studied at [[Hebrew school]] and had a [[Bar Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Breitbart, Republican Jewish media mogul, is dead at 43|first=Jonah|last=Lowenfeld|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/thenon-prophet/item/andrew_breitbart_republican_jewish_media_mogul_is_dead_at_43_20120301}}</ref> Theologically he was an agnostic.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart attended [[Brentwood School (Los Angeles)|Brentwood School]], one of the country's top private schools, but did not distinguish himself, saying: \"My sense of humor saved me\".<ref name=\"family\"/> However, he discovered that he loved writing, publishing his first comedic piece in the school newspaper, the ''Brentwood Eagle'', analyzing the inequality in his high school's senior and junior parking lots: \"One had Mercedes and BMWs, the other Sciroccos and GTIs.\"\"<ref name=\"family\"/> Breitbart remembers his upbringing as [[apolitical]], except in one instance: when the family's rabbi tried to defend [[Jesse Jackson]] against charges of antisemitism after his \"[[Hymietown]]\" comment, his parents left the synagogue in protest.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart would remain \"proudly and playfully Jewish\" throughout his life, although not always religiously observant. He would sing Hebrew songs at work while also teasing his Orthodox Jewish colleagues for keeping a kosher diet.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/Comment-Andrew-Breitbart-Israel-and-Judaism \"Comment: Andrew Breitbart, Israel and Judaism\"] By Benjamin Weinthal, ''Jerusalem Post'', April 3, 2012</ref> [[Joel Pollak]] wrote: \"He carried his faith as he carried all his convictions: with a lighthearted touch but a deep commitment.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/> Breitbart later said of his profession: \"I'm glad I've become a journalist because I'd like to fight on behalf of the Israeli people... And the Israeli people, I adore and I love.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/><ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/politics/article/andrew_breitbart_the_unabashedly_biased_journalist_20110613/ \"Andrew Breitbart, the unabashedly 'biased journalist'\u201d] by Jonah Lowenfeld, June 13, 2011, ''Jewish Journal''</ref>\n\nWhile in high school, Breitbart worked as a [[pizza delivery]] driver; he sometimes delivered to celebrities such as [[Judge Reinhold]].<ref>''Righteous Indignation'', page 17</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[American studies]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1991, graduating with \"no sense of [his] future whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/29/20070529-111812-9136r/print/|title='News addict' gets his fix|last=McCain|first=Robert Stacy|date=May 29, 2007|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> His early jobs included a stint at [[cable television|cable]] channel [[E! Entertainment Television]], working for the company's [[blog|online magazine]], and some time in film production.<ref name=\"wsj\"/> He was a Lincoln Fellow at [[Claremont Institute|The Claremont Institute]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|last=DeVore|first=Chuck|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2012/mar/01/andrew-breitbart-most-important-conservative|title=The most important conservative of our time never to hold office {{!}} Chuck DeVore|date=2012-03-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.claremont.org/page/fellowships/lincoln-fellowship/former-lincoln-fellows/|title=Lincoln Fellowship Alumni|website=www.claremont.org|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nPreviously left-leaning in his politics, Breitbart changed his political views after experiencing \"an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]]\" while watching the late 1991 [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|confirmation hearings]] for Supreme Court justice [[Clarence Thomas]], due to what he considered unfounded attacks on the part of liberals based on former employee [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment accusations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aim.org/podcast/take-aim-andrew-breitbart/|title= Take AIM: Andrew Breitbart }}</ref> Breitbart later described himself as \"a [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] conservative\" with [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] sympathies.<ref name=\"c-span\"/>\n\nListening to radio hosts such as [[Rush Limbaugh]] helped Breitbart refine his political and philosophical positions, igniting an interest in learning that he had suppressed as a result of his distaste for the \"nihilistic musings of dead [[critical theory|critical theorists]]\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\">Righteous Indignation, p. 36</ref> that had dominated his studies at Tulane. In this era, Breitbart also read [[Camille Paglia]]'s book ''[[Sexual Personae]]'' (1990), a massive survey of Western art, literature and culture from ancient Egypt to the 20th century, which, he wrote, \"made me realize how little I really had learned in college.\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\"/>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===Authorship, research, and reporting===\nBreitbart has been lauded for his role in the \"evolution of pioneering websites\" including ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and ''[[Drudge Report|The Drudge Report]]'', and later his \"Big\" sites. Journalists such as Nick Gillespie and Conor Friedersdorf have credited Breitbart with bringing new voices to debates about politics and culture. Breitbart told ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' in 2004 that after feeling ignored by existing outlets, \"We decided to go out and create our media.\" Described as \"a series of do-it-yourself demonstration projects\" and \"conversation pits\", the Breitbart websites have been both criticized and praised for their role in various political issues.<ref name=Atlantic1 /><ref name=\"Gillespie\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|date=March 2, 2012|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=January 4, 2015|author=Gillespie, Nick}}</ref> Breitbart has been recognized for adopting an inclusive stance with regard to LGBT participation in the conservative movement. He has also been credited with helping to derail [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories about Barack Obama's citizenship]].<ref name=Atlantic1 />\n\nIn 1995, Breitbart saw ''The Drudge Report'' and was so impressed that he e-mailed [[Matt Drudge]]. Breitbart said, \"I thought what he was doing was by far the coolest thing on the Internet. And I still do.\"<ref name=\"huff\" /> Breitbart described himself as \"Matt Drudge's [[bitch (insult)#In reference to men|bitch]]\"<ref name=\"biyatch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html|title=Lists: What's Your Source for That? Where Andrew Breitbart gets his information.|accessdate=October 1, 2008|publisher=ReasonOnline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919111403/http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html| archivedate= September 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> and selected and posted links to other news wire sources. Later, Drudge introduced him to a then still-[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Arianna Huffington]]<ref name=\"wsj\" /> and Breitbart subsequently assisted in the creation of ''The Huffington Post''.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Andrew Breitbart Helped Launch Huffington Post|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/how-andrew-breitbart-helped-launch-huffington-post|publisher=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBreitbart wrote a weekly column for ''[[The Washington Times]]'', which also appeared at [[Real Clear Politics]]. Breitbart also co-wrote the book ''[[Hollywood, Interrupted|Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon]]'' with [[Mark Ebner]], a book that is highly critical of U.S. [[celebrity culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |title=Wiley: Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity \u2013 Andrew Breitbart, Mark Ebner |work=wiley.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705051111/http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |archivedate=July 5, 2009 }}</ref> On January 19, 2011, the [[LGBT conservatism|conservative gay rights]] group [[GOProud]] announced Breitbart had joined its Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%E2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803200215/http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%e2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 3, 2011 |title=Conservative Media Mogul Andrew Breitbart to Join GOProud's Advisory Council |publisher=Goproud.org |date=January 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Grand Central Publishing released Breitbart's book ''Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World'', in which he discussed his own political evolution and the part he took in the rise of [[new media]], most notably at the Drudge Report and ''The Huffington Post''.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Breitbart's websites broke the story that congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] was [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandal|sending women revealing photographs of himself]].<ref>Daly, Corbett D. [http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20069298-503544.html \"Conservative website posts private pictures of Anthony Weiner.\"] [[CBS News]]. June 6, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Breitbart.com===\n{{main|Breitbart News Network}}\nBreitbart launched his first website as a news site; it is often linked to by the ''[[Drudge Report]]'' and other websites. It has wire stories from the [[Associated Press]], [[Reuters]], [[Agence France-Presse]], [[Fox News]], [[PR Newswire]], and [[U.S. Newswire]], as well as direct links to a number of major international newspapers. Its political viewpoint as well as its audience runs to the [[right-wing|right]] within the U.S. political spectrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.org/interactives/media-polarization/outlet/breitbart/|title=Where Breitbart's Audience Fits on the Political Spectrum |date=October 21, 2014|work=Pew Research Center's Journalism Project}}</ref> In 2007, Breitbart launched a video blog, Breitbart.tv.<ref>[[Rob Owen (journalist)|Owen, Rob]]. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07075/769897-96.stm The next wave: Ex-WTAE anchor Scott Baker changes channel to run Web news site], ''[[Post-Gazette]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart and one of his editors [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] were sued for [[defamation]] by [[Shirley Sherrod]], who had been [[Firing of Shirley Sherrod|fired]] after Breitbart posted a video of a speech given by Sherrod. The video had been selectively edited to suggest that she had purposely discriminated against a white farmer, while in reality the unedited video told the story of how she had helped that farmer.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Zeleny| first = Jeff|author2=  Wheaton, Sarah| title = At Gathering, Ron Paul Is No. 1 for 2012| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]| pages = A21 | date = February 13, 2011| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/us/politics/13cpac.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | accessdate =February 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein\" /> Breitbart himself maintained that he stated this in his article about it, and that the purpose of the video was to show the crowd's positive reaction to Sherrod's statements about discriminating against the white farmer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/128436-andrew-breitbart/ |title= Breitbart on ACORN, Sherrod, and 'Gotcha' Journalism |author=Stephen Reader |date= May 11, 2011}}</ref> In July 2015, it was reported that Sherrod and Breitbart's estate had reached a tentative settlement.<ref name=\"Gerstein\">{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Breitbart, Sherrod near libel settlement|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/breitbart-sherrod-near-libel-settlement-209824.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It was reported October 1, 2016, that the lawsuit was settled.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://talkingpointsmemo.com/muckraker/sherrod-breitbart-lawsuit-settle |title= Ex-USDA Official Settles Her Lawsuit Over Breitbart Video That Got Her Fired |work= [[Talking Points Memo]] |author= Tierney Sneed |date= October 1, 2015 |accessdate= October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commentaries===\nIn 2009, Breitbart appeared as a commentator on ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'' and ''[[Dennis Miller]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BREITBART: 'My Real Time With Bill Maher'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/16/my-real-time-with-bill-maher/?page=all|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=March 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he was a guest commentator on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News Channel's]] morning show and frequently appeared as a guest panelist on [[Fox News]]'s late night program, ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]''. Breitbart also appeared as a commentator in the 2004 documentary ''[[Michael Moore Hates America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/212271/michael-wilson-loves-america/andrew-leigh |title=National Review Online|publisher=nationalreview.com |accessdate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2009, Breitbart appeared on the [[C-SPAN]] program ''[[Washington Journal]]''. He gave his opinions on the mainstream media, Hollywood, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama Administration]] and his personal political views, having heated debates with several callers.<ref name=\"c-span\">[http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 Andrew Breitbart, Breitbart.com Publisher] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002155759/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 |date=October 2, 2012 }} [[C-SPAN]], October 22, 2009. Breitbart referred to the \"Democrat-media complex\" several times...</ref>\n\nIn the hours immediately following Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]'s death, Breitbart called Kennedy a \"villain\", a \"duplicitous bastard\", a \"prick\"<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html|title=Not all Kennedy critics hold fire|accessdate=August 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090827091650/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html| archivedate= August 27, 2009| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"a special pile of human excrement,\" adding, \"Sorry, he destroyed lives. And he knew it,\" referring to Kennedy's actions during the [[Chappaquiddick incident]], the [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination]], and the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination]].<ref>\"[http://www.pennlive.com/editorials/index.ssf/2009/08/compromise_what_pennsylvania_l.html Compromise: what Pennsylvania lawmakers could learn from Ted Kennedy]\" (editorial), ''[[The Patriot-News]]'' (Pennsylvania), August 28, 2009. Retrieved September 24, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320 |title=Opinion: Ted Kennedy, the liberal adversary to the conservative movement |publisher=digitaljournal.com |accessdate=September 24, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003110202/http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320| archivedate= October 3, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Breitbart received the [[Reed Irvine]] [[Accuracy in Media]] Award during the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in Washington, D.C. During his acceptance speech, he responded directly to accusations by ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporter Kate Zernike that [[Jason Mattera]], a young conservative activist, had been using \"racial tones\" in his [[allusions]] to President [[Barack Obama]], and had spoken in a \"[[Chris Rock]] voice\". From the podium, Breitbart called Zernike \"a despicable human being\" for having made such allegations about what, according to him, was just Mattera's Brooklyn accent.<ref>Beam, Christopher, [http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.html \"'Media Is Everything. It's Everything.' Slate's 2010 profile of Andrew Breitbart\"], ''Slate.com'', March 15, 2010.</ref> At the same conference, Breitbart was also filmed saying to journalist [[Max Blumenthal]] that he found him to be \"a jerk\" and \"a despicable human being\" over a blog entry in which Blumenthal accused Breitbart of employing a racist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MIeByOeERpY |title=Max Blumenthal confronted by Andrew Breitbart and Larry O'Connor/Stage right at CPAC 10 |publisher=YouTube |date=February 20, 2010 |accessdate=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Blumenthal was referring to [[James O'Keefe]] over his having attended a [[Georgetown Law Center]] discussion on race featuring Kevin Martin, [[John Derbyshire]], and [[Jared Taylor]], the last of whom founded ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', an online magazine often considered white supremacist. Neither O'Keefe nor Breitbart endorsed Taylor's views.\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart said that \"of course\" [[Donald Trump]] was not a conservative, adding:\n\n<blockquote>But this is a message to those candidates who are languishing at 2 percent and 3 percent within the Republican Party who are brand names in Washington, but the rest of the country don't know ... celebrity is everything in this country. And if these guys don't learn how to play the media the way that Barack Obama played the media last election cycle and the way that Donald Trump is playing the election cycle, we're going to probably get a celebrity candidate.<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\">{{cite news|last1=Weigel|first1=David|title=Five things to know about Breitbart, the new force in the Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/17/five-things-to-know-about-breitbart-the-new-force-in-the-trump-campaign/|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThese comments resurfaced after the controversy of Donald Trump hiring [[Breitbart News]]' executive chairman [[Steve Bannon]] to be his [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\" />\n\n===Activism===\n{{See also|Tea party movement#Reports of slurs at health care reform protests|l1=Tea Party movement}}\nBreitbart often appeared as a speaker at [[Tea Party movement]] events across the U.S. For example, Breitbart was a speaker at the first National Tea Party Convention at Gaylord Opryland Hotel in Nashville on February 6, 2010.<ref>\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_D2YLnaTr6w/ Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, February 2010]{{dead link|date=March 2012 | Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, January]\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N3os3js4B0/ Part 2]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3t6XSeR5GEw/ Part 3]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jJZmKGE6tdE/ Part 4]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> Breitbart later involved himself in a controversy over allegations of [[homophobia|homophobic]] and [[racism|racial]] slurs being used at a March 20, 2010, rally at the [[United States Capitol]] in Washington, D.C., by asserting that slurs were never used, and that \"it was a set-up\" by [[Nancy Pelosi]] and the Democratic Party. Breitbart offered to donate $100,000 to the [[United Negro College Fund]] \"for any audio/video footage of the [[nigger|N-word]] being hurled,\" claiming that the several Congressmen made it up. Breitbart insisted Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] and several other witnesses were forced to lie, concluding that \"Nancy Pelosi did a great disservice to a great civil rights icon by thrusting him out there to perform this mischievous task. His reputation is now on the line as a result of her desperation to take down the Tea Party movement.\"<ref name=\"AB-100402\">{{cite web |url=http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |title=Barack Obama's Helter-Skelter, Insane Clown Posse, Alinsky Plans to 'Deconstruct' America |first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |publisher=Big Journalism |date=April 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302143429/http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |archivedate=March 2, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WPost Omb\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/09/AR2010040903716.html|title=Allegations of spitting and slurs at Capitol protest merit more reporting|date=April 11, 2010|work=Washington Post|accessdate=April 14, 2010| first=Andrew |last=Alexander}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a [[YouTube]] video showed Breitbart yelling at [[Occupy D.C.]] protesters outside a Washington hotel hosting a [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC). The video showed security escorting Breitbart back to the hotel while he told the protesters to \"behave yourself\", and alluding to reported assaults of women at Occupy encampments, he repeatedly yelled, \"Stop raping people\", and called the protestors \"filthy, filthy, raping, murdering freaks!\" David Carr said with the incident Breitbart had caused his last \"viral storm on the Web.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html?pagewanted=all |work=The New York Times |first=David |last=Carr |title=The Life and Death of Andrew Breitbart |date=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=CPAC>Sources that describe the confrontation with Occupy protesters at CPAC 2012:\n* [http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2012/02/web-talking-about-andrew-breitbarts-occupy-DC-freakout/48598/ The Web is Talking About Andrew Breitbart's Occupy D.C. Freakout], by Seth Abramovitch, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', February 12, 2012\n* [http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2012/02/11/eighty_seven_seconds_of_andrew_breitbart_yelling.html Eighty-Seven Seconds of Andrew Breitbart Yelling], by David Weigel, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', February 11, 2012\n* [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers WATCH: Andrew Breitbart LOSES It On Occupy Wall Street Protesters]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212021939/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers |date=December 12, 2012 }}, by Grace Wyler, ''[[Business Insider]]'', March 6, 2012\n* [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/03/01/andrew-breitbart-dies-most-controversial-moments-video.html Andrew Breitbart Dies: Most Controversial Moments (Video)], by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://www.observer.com/2012/03/andrew-breitbart-dead-03012012/ Andrew Breitbart Dead at 43], by Kat Stoeffel and Hunter Walker, ''[[The New York Observer]]'', January 3, 2012\n* [http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ EXCLUSIVE VIDEO: Blogger Andrew Breitbart to Occupiers: 'Stop Raping People!']   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419075311/http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ |date=April 19, 2012 }}, by Emily Crockett, ''[[Campus Progress]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/andrew-breitbart-confronts-occupy-crowd-at-cpac-demands-they-stop-raping-people/ Andrew Breitbart Confronts Occupy Crowd At CPAC, Demands They 'Stop Raping People'], by Frances Martel, ''[[Mediaite]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php Right-Wing Blog Mogul Andrew Breitbart Flips Out at Occupy D.C. Outside CPAC]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212061609/http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php |date=February 12, 2012 }}, by Benjamin R. Freed, ''[[DCist]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php Occupiers Berated By Breitbart; ''Times'' Looks At Movement's Next Moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413053517/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php |date=April 13, 2012 }}, by Esther Zuckerman, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', February 11, 2012</ref>\n\nBreitbart appeared posthumously in ''[[Occupy Unmasked]]'', a documentary film by [[Steve Bannon]] that contends that the [[Occupy movement|Occupy Wall Street movement]] of \"largely na\u00efve students and legitimately concerned citizens looking for answers\" is actually orchestrated by sinister, violent, and organized leaders with the purpose of not just changing, but destroying the American government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Occupyunmasked.com|url=http://www.occupyunmasked.com/about.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBreitbart was married to Susannah Bean, the daughter of actor [[Orson Bean]] and fashion designer Carolyn Maxwell, and had four children.<ref name=\"huff\"/><ref name=\"Saad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-orson-bean-2050-story.html |first1=Nardine |last1=Saad |date=February 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=OBITUARIES Actor Orson Bean, local theater mainstay who rose to fame as a 1950s TV personality, dies |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AP\"> {{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-114135652.html |title=Celebrity Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 8, 2020|via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of February 29, 2012, Breitbart collapsed suddenly while walking in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]]. He was rushed to [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]], where he was pronounced dead just after midnight, March 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html |title=The Provocateur | publisher =New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Celebs/breitbart,%20andrew_report.pdf |title=Andrew Breitbart autopsy report | publisher =Autopsyfile.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337\n |title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead\n |first=Christina |last=Ng |date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> He was 43 years old. An [[autopsy]] by the [[Los Angeles County Coroner's Office]] showed that he had [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]], with focal coronary [[atherosclerosis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/05/commentator-and-editor-andrew-breitbart-died-of-heart-failure-and-hard-up-to-a-60-narrowing-of-a-major-artery-and-was-unde.html|title=Andrew Breitbart died of heart failure, narrowing of artery, coroner finds|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|work=L.A. Times|publisher=L.A. Times|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and died of a [[heart attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|date=2012-03-01|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His burial was in the Jewish cemetery [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery|Hillside Memorial Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew James Breitbart |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/86040288/andrew-james-breitbart |website=Find A Grave\u2122 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn remembrance, Republican presidential candidates [[Rick Santorum]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Newt Gingrich]] praised Breitbart.<ref name=\"media star\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/03/06/limbaugh-and-the-gop-the-media-stars-and-politics/agdmwrt/?page=3|title=Limbaugh and the GOP: The media stars and politics|author=Beth Fouhey|author2=Philip Elliott|work=Associated Press|date=March 6, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> Santorum called Breitbart's death \"a huge loss\" that strongly affected him.<ref name=\"media star\"/><ref>{{cite video |date=March 1, 2012 |title=CBS News|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/andrew-breitbart-death-shocks-santorum-100/2012/03/01/gIQAqm8qkR_video.html}}</ref> Romney praised Breitbart as a \"fearless conservative,\" while Gingrich remembered him as \"the most innovative pioneer in conservative activist social media in America\".<ref name=\"media star\" /> A special episode of ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]'' aired the day after his death as the host and panelists paid their tributes and showed clips from his appearances on the show.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CLqEPe9emsU |title=Red Eye Remembers Andrew Breitbart |accessdate= September 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|title = Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World|publisher = [[Grand Central Publishing]]|date = April 15, 2011|isbn = 978-0-446-57282-8|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/righteousindigna0000brei|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first = Mark C.|last =  Ebner|authorlink = Mark Ebner |author2=Andrew Breitbart |title = [[Hollywood, Interrupted]]: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|date = March 10, 2005|isbn = 978-0-471-70624-3}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q503917|q=Andrew Breitbart|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|c=category:Andrew Breitbart}}\n* {{IMDb name|1620485}}\n* {{C-SPAN|andrewbreitbart}}\n* {{Worldcat id|id=lccn-no2004-14171}}\n* {{Find a Grave|86040288}}\n\n{{Andrew Breitbart|state=expanded}}\n{{Portalbar|Biography|California|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breitbart, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American alternative journalists]]\n[[Category:American blogg